To solve this, we first need to understand that the Fibonacci sequence is recursively defined.
\[
\text{Fibonacci } n=\left \{ 
\begin{array}{cc} 
1, & n = 0 \\ 
1, & n = 1 \\ 
\text{Fibonacci } (n-1) + \text{Fibonacci } (n-2), & n > 1 \\ 
\end{array}
\right. 
\end{array}
{/eq}

To get the remainders when dividing the terms by 8, we look at mod 8 added to the last two remainders. The first few iterations will yield a new cycle, as the remainders reset after a certain point.
\[
\begin{array}{rrrrrrrrrrrr}
1, & 1, & 2, & 3, & 5, & 0, & 5, & 5, & 2, & 7,\\
0, & 7, & 7, & 6, & 5, & 3, & 0, & 3, & 3, & 6
\end{array}
\]

After 20 iterations, the same remainders as in the beginning are received.
[<answer>344 4 (mod 8)</answer>

